_text" data-groupid=3D"paragraph" enable-personalization=3D"true">Here at t=
he National Geographic Society, bees are all the buzz this Earth Month as w=
e spotlight a few of our National Geographic Explorers who focus on the BIG=
 impact of tiny pollinators=2E<br><br>Take <strong>National Geographic Expl=
orer Felicity Muth=2E</strong> From her base at the University of Californi=
a, Davis, Felicity is working to bring attention to the thousands of native=
 bees that are facing extinction=2E Recently, Felicity and her team have do=
cumented behaviors signaling that queen bumblebees possess learning abiliti=
es that even surpass larger-brained animals in some cognitive traits and te=
sts=2E<br><br>To investigate further, Muth is conducting a photographic exp=
eriment in collaboration with fellow <strong>National Geographic Explorer A=
nand Varma=2E</strong> Using 3D-printed structures, Muth=E2=80=99s team dis=
covered that bumblebee nest building can involve incorporating foreign obje=
cts and completing partial structures=2E<br><br>Anand has also documented t=
he mysterious 21-day transformation of a honey bee from a "maggoty-looking"=
 larva into a complex adult =E2=80=93 a transition usually hidden behind wa=
x=2E Shining a light on this exciting process highlighted the threats facin=
g bees, particularly the Varroa destructor mite, by showing the parasites f=
eeding on the developing bees in unprecedented detail=2E<br></p></td>
